import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

scores_columns = [
    'Code_Switching_Score',
    'Complexity_Score',
    'Emotional_Intensity_Score',
    'Formality_Score',
    'Sentimental_Score'
]
category_column = 'Category'

categories = df[category_column].unique()

if len(categories) != 2:
    raise ValueError("The t-test requires exactly two categories in the classification variable.")

group1 = df[df[category_column] == categories[0]]
group2 = df[df[category_column] == categories[1]]

t_test_results = {}
for score in scores_columns:
    t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(group1[score], group2[score], equal_var=False)
    t_test_results[score] = {'t_stat': t_stat, 'p_value': p_value}

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.histplot(group1[score], color='blue', label=f"{categories[0]}", kde=True, stat="density")
    sns.histplot(group2[score], color='orange', label=f"{categories[1]}", kde=True, stat="density")
    plt.title(f'Histogram of {score} by {category_column}')
    plt.xlabel(score)
    plt.ylabel('Density')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

t_test_results

import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

score_columns = [
    'Code_Switching_Score',
    'Complexity_Score',
    'Emotional_Intensity_Score',
    'Formality_Score',
    'Sentimental_Score'
]

regression_results = {}

for score in score_columns:
    X = df[['Category_2']]
    y = df[score]

    X = sm.add_constant(X)
    
    model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    regression_results[score] = model

    print(f"Regression Summary for {score}:")
    print(model.summary())

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    sns.regplot(x='Category_2', y=score, data=df, ci=None, line_kws={'color': 'red'})
    plt.title(f"Regression Analysis: {score} vs. Category_2")
    plt.xlabel('Category_2')
    plt.ylabel(score)
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

Code Interpretation score_columns: The list contains five dependent variables that need to be regressed.

Regression Analysis: Use statsmodels's OLS (Ordinary Least Squares) to fit the model, with Category_2 as the independent variable and the five scores as dependent variables.

Regression Visualization: Use seaborn.regplot to draw a scatter plot and regression line for each dependent variable and Category_2.

Regression Results: In the code, model.summary() prints the statistical results of each regression model, including coefficients, standard errors, t values, p values, and R-squared.

Regression analysis conclusion: Except for the formality_score score, which is not significantly different (p=0.743), the other scores are significantly different. The emotional_intensity_score score generally shows creativity>current affairs, and the other three scores are all current affairs>cretivity.

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

X = df[['Complexity_Score', 'Code_Switching_Score', 'Formality_Score', 'Emotional_Intensity_Score', 'Sentimental_Score']]

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42)
df['cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(X)

sns.scatterplot(
    x='Complexity_Score',
    y='Code_Switching_Score',
    hue='cluster',
    data=df,
    palette='viridis'
)
plt.title('K-Means Clustering: Complexity Score vs Code-Switching Score')
plt.show()

sns.scatterplot(
    x='Emotional_Intensity_Score',
    y='Code_Switching_Score',
    hue='cluster',
    data=df,
    palette='viridis'
)
plt.title('K-Means Clustering: Complexity Score vs Code-Switching Score')
plt.show()


pca = PCA(n_components=2)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X)
df['pca1'], df['pca2'] = X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1]

sns.scatterplot(
    x='pca1',
    y='pca2',
    hue='cluster',
    data=df,
    palette='viridis'
)
plt.title('PCA Visualization of Clusters')
plt.show()

sns.scatterplot(
    x='pca1',
    y='pca2',
    hue='Category',
    data=df,
    palette='Set2'
)
plt.title('PCA Visualization by Category')
plt.show()

sns.pairplot(
    df,
    vars=['Complexity_Score', 'Code_Switching_Score', 'Formality_Score', 'Emotional_Intensity_Score', 'Sentimental_Score'],
    hue='cluster',
    palette='viridis',
    diag_kind='kde'
)
plt.suptitle('Pairplot of All Variables Colored by K-Means Clusters', y=1.02)
plt.show()
